  "prompt": "How do you do \"inline if\" in JavaScript?",
  "response": "In JavaScript, \"inline if\" typically refers to the use of the conditional (ternary) operator, which is a shorthand for the `if-else` statement. The syntax of the ternary operator is:\n\n```javascript\ncondition ? expressionIfTrue : expressionIfFalse;\n```\n\nHere's how you can use it:\n\n```javascript\nlet age = 18;\nlet canVote = (age >= 18) ? \"You can vote.\" : \"You cannot vote.\";\nconsole.log(canVote); // Output: \"You can vote.\"\n```\n\nIn this example, if `age` is greater than or equal to 18, `canVote` will be assigned the string \"You can vote.\"; otherwise, it will be assigned \"You cannot vote.\" \n\nYou can use this operator to simplify code when you need to assign a value based on a condition. However, for more complex conditions or actions, it's usually better to use a standard `if-else` block for readability.",
